<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-492-559  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 492 559.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 1 1990 v4 n35 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pentagon's info technology budget to favor systems integration.andO;(Department of Defense to allocate significant funding to systemsintegrators) (Frost andamp; Sullivan Inc.'s US Military Market forDefense Department Systems Integration report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marsan, Carolyn Duffy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Defense (DOD) will increase its spending forinformation technology significantly through 1996, particularlyfor systems integrators.andP;  A study by Frost and Sullivan Incpredicts that DOD systems integration will emerge as a growth areain the otherwise stagnant defense market.andP;  Factors influencing theincrease in systems integration expenditures include themilitary's shift toward commercial computer products, open systemsbased on the Government Open Systems Interconnection Profilestandard, and the Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Supportprogram, which will automate the design, development andacquisition of weapons systems.andP;  Frost and Sullivan attributes themove toward systems integration services primarily to DOD'sCorporate Information Management initiative, an effort by DefenseSecretary Dick Cheney to standardize various military informationsystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Frost and Sullivan Inc. (Reports).andO;Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseComputer Systems IntegratorsOffice AutomationForecastingMarket AnalysisGovernment AgencyMilitaryReportsEquipment AcquisitionSystem DevelopmentPlanning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>